# Event Scheduling and Conflict Resolution System

A comprehensive event scheduling system implemented in **four different programming paradigms** to demonstrate diverse approaches to solving the same problem. This project showcases imperative, object-oriented, functional, and logic programming paradigms.

## üìã Overview

This system manages event scheduling with automatic conflict detection for:
- **Location conflicts**: Multiple events scheduled in the same location at overlapping times
- **Resource conflicts**: Multiple events requiring the same resource at overlapping times

## üéØ Features

- ‚úÖ Add new events with validation
- ‚úÖ View all events or only conflicting events
- ‚úÖ Edit existing events (title, time, location, resource, description)
- ‚úÖ Delete events with confirmation
- ‚úÖ Automatic conflict detection and re-evaluation
- ‚úÖ Chronological schedule display
- ‚úÖ Filter events by resource
- ‚úÖ Detailed conflict reports with resolution guidance

## üîß Implementations

### 1. **Imperative Paradigm (C)**
**File:** `EventSchedulingSystem.c`

**Characteristics:**
- Uses global variables and state
- Imperative control structures (for loops, while loops)
- Direct memory manipulation with arrays
- Step-by-step procedural approach

**Compilation & Execution:**
```bash
gcc EventSchedulingSystem.c -o EventSchedulingSystem
./EventSchedulingSystem
```

---

### 2. **Object-Oriented Paradigm (Java)**
**File:** `EventSchedulingSystem.java`

**Characteristics:**
- Encapsulation of data and methods in classes
- Inheritance and polymorphism
- Object composition (ScheduleManager contains Events)
- Method overriding (toString)

**Compilation & Execution:**
```bash
javac EventSchedulingSystem.java
java EventSchedulingSystem
```

---

### 3. **Functional Paradigm (Common Lisp)**
**File:** `event_schedule.lisp`

**Characteristics:**
- Pure functions without side effects
- Immutable data structures
- Higher-order functions (map, filter, reduce)
- Recursive operations
- Minimal global state

**Execution:**
```bash
# Using SBCL (Steel Bank Common Lisp)
sbcl --load event_schedule.lisp

# Or using CLISP
clisp event_schedule.lisp
```

---

### 4. **Logic Programming Paradigm (GNU Prolog)**
**File:** `event_schedule.pl`

**Characteristics:**
- Declarative rules and facts
- Unification and backtracking
- Pattern matching
- Logic-based conflict detection
- Database-like knowledge base

**Compilation & Execution:**
```bash
# Compile
gplc event_schedule.pl

# Run compiled version
./event_schedule

# Or run in interpreter
gprolog --consult-file event_schedule.pl
```

---

## üìù Usage Guide

### Adding an Event

All implementations follow the same workflow:

1. Select **"Add New Event"** from the menu
2. Enter event details:
   - **Title**: Name of the event
   - **Start Time**: Format `HH:MM` (24-hour)
   - **End Time**: Format `HH:MM` (24-hour)
   - **Location**: Room or venue name
   - **Resource**: Professor name, equipment, etc.
   - **Description**: Brief description

### Example Input

```
Event Title: Database Lecture
Start Time: 09:00
End Time: 10:30
Location: Room 101
Resource: Prof. Smith
Description: Introduction to SQL
```

### Editing an Event

1. Select **"Edit Event"** from the menu
2. View the list of all events with their IDs
3. Enter the ID of the event to edit
4. Choose what to edit:
   - Individual fields (title, time, location, resource, description)
   - All fields at once
5. Enter new values
6. System automatically re-evaluates conflicts

### Deleting an Event

1. Select **"Delete Event"** from the menu
2. View the list of all events with their IDs
3. Enter the ID of the event to delete
4. Confirm deletion (yes/no)
5. System automatically re-evaluates conflicts

### Viewing Conflicts

Select **"Detect and Display Conflicts"** to see:
- Conflict type (Location or Resource)
- Conflicting events with details
- Resolution guidance

### Filtering Events

Select **"Filter Events by Resource"** and enter a resource name to view all events using that resource.

---

## üèóÔ∏è System Architecture

### Data Structures

Each implementation represents events with:
- **ID**: Unique identifier
- **Title**: Event name
- **Start Time**: Hour and minute
- **End Time**: Hour and minute
- **Location**: Venue
- **Resource**: Required resource
- **Description**: Event details
- **Conflict Status**: Boolean flag

### Conflict Detection Algorithm

```
For each pair of events (i, j):
  If time_overlap(i, j):
    If same_location(i, j):
      Mark as LOCATION CONFLICT
    If shared_resource(i, j):
      Mark as RESOURCE CONFLICT
```

---

## üîç Paradigm Comparison

| Feature | Imperative (C) | OOP (Java) | Functional (Lisp) | Logic (Prolog) |
|---------|----------------|------------|-------------------|----------------|
| **State Management** | Global variables | Object encapsulation | Minimal global state | Dynamic facts |
| **Data Structure** | Arrays | Objects/Classes | Structs/Lists | Facts/Rules |
| **Control Flow** | Loops, conditionals | Methods, polymorphism | Recursion, higher-order | Unification, backtracking |
| **Conflict Detection** | Nested loops | Object methods | Pure functions | Logical predicates |
| **Code Reusability** | Functions | Inheritance, composition | Pure functions | Rule definitions |
| **Memory Management** | Manual | Automatic (GC) | Automatic (GC) | Automatic |

---

## ‚öôÔ∏è Requirements

### C Implementation
- GCC compiler (or any C compiler)
- Standard C library

### Java Implementation
- JDK 8 or higher
- Java Runtime Environment

### Common Lisp Implementation
- SBCL (Steel Bank Common Lisp) or
- CLISP or
- Any Common Lisp implementation

### Prolog Implementation
- GNU Prolog
- SWI-Prolog (alternative)

---

## üêõ Error Handling

All implementations include:
- ‚úÖ Time validation (hours 0-23, minutes 0-59)
- ‚úÖ Start time must be before end time
- ‚úÖ Input format validation
- ‚úÖ Non-existent event ID handling
- ‚úÖ Graceful error messages

---

## üìä Sample Output

```
========================================
CONFLICT DETECTION AND RESOLUTION REPORT
========================================

Conflict 1: Location Overlap
Type: Location Double-Booking
Location: Room 101
Conflicting Events:
  - [ID:1] Database Lecture (09:00 - 10:30)
  - [ID:2] AI Workshop (10:00 - 11:30)
Resolution Guidance:
  - Relocate one event to an available room
  - Adjust event times to avoid overlap
```

